<div id='gazette_story'>
    <div align='center'>
        <font size='4'><b>Who had the Winning Spirit?</b></font><br>
                                <img src='http://graphics.millsberry.com/site_gfx/interiors/gazette/gazette_20090813.jpg' border='1' width='280' height='200'>
                        </div>
        <div id='gazette_byline'><em>By Audrey Smythe-Wei<br>Editor-in-Chief</em></div>
        <b>Thursday, August 13, 2009</b> &mdash;
    In the heart of the <a href="http://millsberry.com/home/?user=edna_30">Golden Valley neighborhood</a>, Millsberry citizens gathered &#039;round as a new house was going up. It was quaint&mdash;and pink&mdash;and it was being built for none other than...Edna Nelson! Why the new pad? Because of your votes! That&#039;s right: Edna is the proud winner of the Millsberry Spirit Award, an honor that scores her a shiny golden trophy, plus a <a href="http://millsberry.com/home/?user=edna_30">new home</a>, with lots of cool furniture and other stuff inside! <br><br>And what does that mean for you, a regular Millsberrian? Well, some of Edna&#039;s favorite new pieces will be on sale at the <a href="http://millsberry.com/shop.phtml?shop_id=3">Furniture Store</a>, which means you can have a hint of Edna&#039;s style&mdash;right in your own home! Place a <a href="http://millsberry.com/shop.phtml?shop_id=3">paisley-and-checkered wing chair</a> in your living room. Add an antique <a href="http://millsberry.com/shop.phtml?shop_id=3">side-table</a> next to your bed. Or alert your pals that it&#039;s dinnertime with your very own <a href="http://millsberry.com/shop.phtml?shop_id=3">seven foot tall grandmother clock</a>!<br>
<br>
One citizen exclaimed, &quot;My home immediately felt cozier with the Edna-inspired pieces. The clock took a little getting used to, what with the loud gong going off every hour. But now it&#039;s quite comforting.&quot;<br><br>Despite all of the other stellar nominees, the race for the Spirit Award wasn&#039;t too tight. Edna Nelson, curator of the Millsberry historical society and Millsberry&#039;s oldest and most-beloved citizen, won by a landslide. <br><br>We caught up wth Edna to find out just how many times she had to sing her campaign cheer. She laughed and said, &quot;Oh just a few. After a while, I had to record it to preserve my voice. Also, I didn&#039;t want it to get too annoying. That&#039;s why I eventually switched tactics, and started putting up cookie- and lemonade-stands to make it easy for people to ask me questions about the myths and history surrounding Millsberry.&quot;<br><br>Well, Edna&#039;s quiet charm certainly seems to have worked! Even today, as she brainstormed about decorating her new home, she set up a new lemonade stand and quenched the thirst of the speedy workers helping to construct her home in the heart of Golden Valley. <br><br>Beaming, Edna said, &quot;I&#039;m so excited to see my new house! I&#039;ve lived in just about every neighborhood in Millsberry except for Golden Valley. It&#039;s such a scenic and lush landscape, full of small farms and rolling hills! I&#039;m still in shock that I won the Spirit Award, considering the tough competition. All of the nominees are my friends, and they&#039;re all very talented individuals who add great energy to our town. But we&#039;ll do it again next year. In the meantime, I&#039;m looking forward to getting to know my new neighborhood!&quot;<br><br>As we thanked her for her time, Edna added, &quot;This is what I love about Millsberry&mdash;there&#039;s always something new popping up, something new to explore&mdash;another neighborhood, a new game!&quot;<br><br>Well, if Millsberry&#039;s oldest citizen can find so much fresh stuff to enjoy, this town is definitely full of treasures&mdash;so get out and explore!<br>
    </div>

